What a trigger is

Apex code that fires automatically when a DML operation happens on an sObject. Conceptually it's a database hook — closest analogue in your world is a Postgres trigger or a Mongoose pre/post middleware, except it always runs in bulk (Salesforce processes records in batches of up to 200 per invocation).

apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert, before update, after insert, after update) {
    // routing logic here
}

One trigger per object is the near-universal convention — multiple triggers on the same object have nondeterministic execution order.


Trigger events

Event	                                    Fires
before insert	                            after validation rules pass, before record written to DB
after insert	                            after commit to DB (still in same transaction), record has an Id
before update	                            before the update is written
after update	                            after the update is written
before delete	                            before removal
after delete	                            after removal
after undelete	                            when a record is restored from the Recycle Bin

There is no before undelete. Delete events only give you the old state; insert events only give you the new state.



Context variables

Four you'll use constantly, plus the boolean flags on Trigger:

Trigger.new — List<sObject> of the new versions. Writable in before contexts only.
Trigger.old — List<sObject> of the versions as they existed prior. Always read-only.
Trigger.newMap — Map<Id, sObject> keyed by record Id.
Trigger.oldMap — Map<Id, sObject> keyed by record Id.

Plus Trigger.isBefore, isAfter, isInsert, isUpdate, isDelete, isUndelete, Trigger.size, and Trigger.operationType (an enum — cleaner than chaining booleans).


