The one that trips people up: Trigger.newMap is null in before insert — records don't have Ids yet, so there's no key to map on.

The old/new pairing is what makes field-change detection possible:

apex
for (Opportunity opp : Trigger.new) {
    Opportunity oldOpp = Trigger.oldMap.get(opp.Id);
    if (opp.StageName != oldOpp.StageName && opp.StageName == 'Closed Won') {
        // stage transitioned
    }
}

before vs after

Use before when you're modifying fields on the records being saved. Assign directly to Trigger.new and the platform persists it as part of the same save — no DML, no extra governor limit consumption, no recursion risk.

apex
// before insert/update
for (Account a : Trigger.new) {
    a.Name = a.Name.toUpperCase();  // just assign — no update() call
}

Also use before for cross-record validation you want to block the save (addError() on the record), and for before delete to prevent deletion.

Use after when you need something that only exists post-commit:

The record Id (mandatory for before insert — you don't have one yet). Creating child records, junction records, sharing rules.
Roll-up calculations onto parent records.
Firing Platform Events, @future calls, Queueables.
Fields the system populates on save (formula fields, auto-numbers, LastModifiedDate).

Never call update() on Trigger.new inside a before trigger — it's already in the save pipeline, you'll get a recursion error or wasted DML. And in after contexts Trigger.new is read-only; modifying a record in after update requires an explicit update DML against a fresh copy, which re-fires the trigger. That's where the static-boolean recursion guard pattern comes in.

The patterns that matter for you

Bulkify everything. Triggers receive up to 200 records. No SOQL or DML inside a for loop, ever — collect Ids into a Set, query once outside the loop, build a Map, iterate. Same instinct as avoiding N+1 in your Mongo/Postgres work, but here it's a hard limit (100 SOQL, 150 DML per transaction) that throws an uncatchable LimitException.

Handler pattern. Keep the trigger file as a thin router; put logic in a separate handler class. Testable, and it keeps the one-trigger-per-object rule from producing a 900-line file.

apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert, before update, after insert, after update) {
    AccountTriggerHandler.run();  // or new AccountTriggerHandler().run() with a framework base class
}

Order of execution. Triggers are one step in a long chain: system validation → before triggers → system validation again → save to DB (not committed) → after triggers → assignment/auto-response/workflow rules → processes and flows → escalation rules → roll-up summaries recalculated → commit. Worth memorizing the full list; a lot of "why did my field revert" bugs live in there.

